{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499274"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1482"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1482"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0,0.77,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33424"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1482"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"779"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49907"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33424"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a lesion on the plantar surface of his right foot. His wife noticed the lesion several weeks ago and it seems to have worsened since then. The patient denies pain, itchiness, bleeding or fevers and was unaware of its presence until his wife pointed it out. His medical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, T2 diabetes mellitus, myocardial infarction (four years ago), squamous cell carcinoma and gout. He takes perindopril, atorvastatin, metformin and allopurinol. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and currently smokes 10 cigarettes daily. He drinks 15 standards of alcohol per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears well and has a blood pressure of 140/100 mmG and pulse 84/min. His BMI is 37. On the plantar aspect of his right foot there is a well defined 1cm diameter ulcerating lesion with an erythematous base and surrounding calloused tissue (Image). A Bueger test is positive and there is loss of vibration sensation in the bony prominence of the first metatarsal head.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying disease process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arterial insufficiency","Squamous cell carcinoma","Diabetes mellitus","Syphilis","Venous insufficiency"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a classical \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic\u003C/strong\u003E foot ulcer. \u0026nbsp;The ulcer has developed over an area of increased pressure (a metatarsal head). \u0026nbsp;Diabetic foot ulcers have a mixed aetiology of part neuropathic and part ischaemic. Risk factors include male sex, having diabetes for \u0026gt;10 years and poor diabetes control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUlcers related to \u003Cstrong\u003Earterial insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E tend to occur distally and often on the tips of the toes. They are typically painful, with increased pain at nighttime. While this patient may likely have arterial insufficiency (as evidenced by a positive Bueger test and preexisting cardiovascular risk factors), it is not the underlying pathology of this ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E occur around the ankle in the \u0027gaiter\u0027 region. They are typically more shallow and have asymmetrical borders\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ulcer has well-defined \u0027punched-out\u0027 edges, whereas \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignant lesions \u003C/strong\u003E(such as Marjolin\u0027s ulcer) tend to have raised and rolled edges.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETabes dorsal\u003C/strong\u003E (syphilis) is a late complication of neurosyphilis. It is expected that the patient would have associated nerve root pain. The patient would likely also be experiencing other symptoms of neurosyphilis such as mood changes, headaches, seizures or gait abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Diabetic foot ulcers occur in patients with peripheral neuropathy on areas of increased pressure."],"references":["Ulcer and Wound Management [Internet]. Therapeutic Guidelines. 2019. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/topicTeaser?guidelinePage=Ulcer+and+Wound+Management\u0026etgAccess=true"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1482"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19425"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19425"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/989e92ff-25ee-45a1-b9b6-9dae962d340a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/989e92ff-25ee-45a1-b9b6-9dae962d340a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":251,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-08T04:51:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T11:24:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1482"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33424"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag